		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1044">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Patricia Brieschke&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4275">All of Me</a>&rdquo; [March 2009] is beautiful, but I&rsquo;m puzzled when she writes of having had &ldquo;four children (a boy and a girl with each husband)&rdquo; and then later says that she took her second husband at the age of fifty.</p>

<p>It is hard to fathom how, with her body ravaged by an eating disorder, she had two children after fifty years of age. If she did, then I want to hear that story.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Janie Savage<br>Waynesville, North Carolina</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="1045">
								<p><a href="/contributors/patricia-brieschke"><strong>Patricia Brieschke</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p><span>Janie Savage observes correctly that I married my second husband at the age of fifty. My reproductive capacity had come to an end, mostly due to age rather than an eating disorder. My twins &mdash; a gift to my husband, who did not want to adopt &mdash; were born later the same year, when my older children were already in their twenties. The birth couldn&rsquo;t have happened without the help of a young woman from California who donated her eggs. It is, indeed, another story, one full of joy, trepidation, and suspense, but it&rsquo;s my twins&rsquo; story to tell.</span></p>
	</div>


					</div>

